   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"39" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"Kx1" style=3D"background-position:0px -2457px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   random vector
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2943px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   can be computed using the
   formula<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"215" height=
=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq11]" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -1024px;"></span>
</p>

<div class=3D"bproof"><span class=3D"bproof">Proof</span></div>
<div id=3D"idn1" class=3D"clps"><div class=3D"proofline">
<p>The above formula can be derived as
   follows:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"589" heigh=
t=3D"144" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/covariance-matrix__36.png"=
 alt=3D"[eq12]"></span>
</p>
</div></div>
<p>
   This formula also makes clear that the covariance matrix exists and is
   well-defined only as long as the vector of expected values
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"33" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq13]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2554px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   and the matrix of second  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamenta=
ls-of-probability/cross-moments">cross-moments</a>
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"50" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq14]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2262px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   exist and are well-defined.
</p>
